    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1239456477" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1239456477" />
    <a title="Emma Iadanza" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27230324-emma-iadanza"><img alt="Emma Iadanza" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602279043p2/27230324.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1239456477?book_show_action=true">Mar 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emma Iadanza" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emma Iadanza" href="/user/show/27230324-emma-iadanza">Emma Iadanza</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27230324-emma-iadanza?shelf=favorite-fiction">favorite-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1239456477" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7125924546759931049">Yeah, no. <br/><br/>This is the book that introduced me to the Medici and pageantry and all the things that I will spend the rest of my life researching and teaching and writing about. But equally those studies have made me see the gross number of inaccuracies in this book (which I just as equally love with a great fondness as I despise for those inaccuracies).<br/><br/>A large number of them are simply from poor editing. The fall of Constantinople (1453) is not 4 years after 1439, as Caterina writes. The name of t</span>
  <span id="freeText7125924546759931049" style="display:none">Yeah, no. <br /><br />This is the book that introduced me to the Medici and pageantry and all the things that I will spend the rest of my life researching and teaching and writing about. But equally those studies have made me see the gross number of inaccuracies in this book (which I just as equally love with a great fondness as I despise for those inaccuracies).<br /><br />A large number of them are simply from poor editing. The fall of Constantinople (1453) is not 4 years after 1439, as Caterina writes. The name of the street was Via Larga, not Via Largo, which in itself is a grammatical mistake. There are missing commas. A lot more polishing could have been done. Not to mention the absurdity of a lot of the ideas. For example, although scholars debate the realism of a 'Platonic Academy', the fact is that Plato was not a <em>secret</em> as the characters seem to think he is. Not everyone who read <em>The Republic</em> was suddenly inducted into some secret society. That's not how this works.<br /><br />Besides all that, Caterina has a strange tinge of absurd unrealism to her that made me cringe. Her relationship with her father and son felt constantly inappropriate, more like a lover to both of them. It's creepy for a mother to follow her son to the equivalent of college and the rest of his career just because he was taken from her once. And her writing about her own femininity felt as if it was written by a man, not a woman. It made me uncomfortable to read, as a woman myself.<br /><br />And yet. I still love it. I'm crying a little.<br /><br />Also. Why is the cover for a book about Leonardo ... a Raphael?<br /><br />[2015 review]<br /><br />Before I tear it to shreds let me just say <em>how much</em> I loved this book.<br /><br />I LOVED THIS BOOK SO MUCH.<br />I read it for the first time in December 2013/January 2014 for my English class, in which I had to read a historical fiction novel and then write journals as one of the characters. My parents suggested it to me, and I read it in a single weekend. At the time I had no idea about the Renaissance at all, I was obsessed with opera and I had previously adored ancient Egypt. Anyway - I discovered Lorenzo de' Medici and wrote the journals as him, indulging in the history. I asked my teacher if I should stick to the Fact or to the Fiction - she wouldn't know the difference anyway (we'll get to that later).<br />Then I discovered the rest of Florence. I had already known about Dante but Giotto and Botticelli and EVERTHING and I did my own research and now I own a wide variety of books about this topic ranging from <em>Coniurationis Commentarium</em> by Poliziano to a picture book called "Lorenzo the Magnificent" and Vasari's <em>Lives</em> in Italian.<br />I geek out about the Renaissance like most young girl geeks geek out about Harry Potter or Sherlock. I love Giuliano de' Medici just as they love Benedict Cummberbatch! I went to Florence and saw his tomb, and his house, and the place where he was murdered on Easter for Easter mass! Without this book, I would not love what I love as much as I love it now.<br />And I was so happy that Robin Maxwell wrote this, reading it for the second time, I just got so excited and I wrote her a fan email, and she replied!! I was so excitable reading this that whenever a character I thought about walked into the room, I would literally jump off my bed and do a little dance and then sit down and read more.<br /><br />But now that my praise is over, time for the criticisms. And I have quite a few - they are not specifically of the writing, which is perfectly fine as it is, but more of the historical accuracy and other such things. My one criticism about her writing is how she tends to have sentences that don't have subjects. For example - "I didn't wash the dishes. Do the laundry. Go to the supermarket." A comma could've been easily used.<br /><br />The beginning is my favorite part. It has all my favorite characters, all my favorite people! There is no plot, but it is just so exciting! Everything began to go downhill when Giuliano de' Medici, my favorite, was murdered. I knew it was coming - I'm an expert on the Pazzi Conspiracy. Robin Maxwell explained it rather well, without all the weird political details. She even got the detail about Giuliano's shirt right! It was blue :)<br /><br />The Platonic Academy pleased me so much. It had since the first time I read it, now my friends and I have our own Platonic Academy (on hiatus right now). Unfortunately there were quite a few inaccuracies. Pico della Mirandola did not come to Florence until after 1480, and he appeared in this academy some time before 1478 (at least). In the book, Caterina/Cato notes that Poliziano was in love with Lorenzo. While this may have been true, Pico della Mirandola and Poliziano were known to have been in love - and they were later <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1577958/Medici-philosophers-mystery-death-is-solved.html" rel="nofollow noopener">murdered by order of Piero di Lorenzo de' Medici</a>.<br /><br />Next - Savonarola. I hate him so much! Nonetheless, he *was* a major player in Florence and is important to this story. In the book, all of Florence seems to hate him - incorrect ! Many Florentines loved him and adored him, even though they later decided they were wrong. In fact, Sandro Botticelli was a major supporter of him. He may have burned his painting for show - that really happened - but he <em>actually</em> supported him. That's why his later art is suddenly so religious.<br />I wish that the plot included Savonarola's ordeal by fire, in which he was challenged to walk through the flames to see whether or not he was a false prophet- but it rained. It was true that they used the strappado on him before burning him (and two other monks) at the stake. I hate him and spat on the memorial where they commemorate his burning.<br /><br />Furthermore, all of Florence hated the Borgia Pope (they often just called him "the Borgia") more than they hated Savonarola. When Alexander excommunicated him, they were not happy - but rather upset. In fact, Medici supporters supported Savonarola more than Alexander because he was reform for the church - in fact, Lorenzo de' Medici had been involved in calling Savonarola to Florence in the first place. It is also true that Savonarola did Lorenzo's last rites and absolved him of his sins.<br /><br />This book showed me only the great sides of these two families, the Borgias and the Medici, I believe. It jaded me - I now know that both families were widely hated, that's why so many of them were murdered! But still - I love this book. But it is not true that ALL of Florence supported the Medici - no, many of them absolutely hated them. Cosimo de' Medici was exiled for good reason, they believed - but they later realized they needed him back. And, see, once Lorenzo was gone, Florence dissipated again.<br /><br />Speaking of Lorenzo's death, Lucrezia, his mother, was not alive at the time - she died in the 1480s, after Giuliano.<br /><br />I love the idea of Lorenzo's library open to the public - although in reality it may not have been. I went into the room in Palazzo Medici, now a dark, forsaken empty place on the first floor of the not-so-great palazzo (except for Gozzoli's frescos which are AMAZING). It was a wonderful large room, I can't imagine the great works it once held! Caterina keeps talking about "completing the library" - this may have been taken from a real quote by Lorenzo said to one of his close friends on his deathbed. "If only I could have lived to see our library completed!"<br /><br />But, alas, the book has come to a close. Thank you, Robin Maxwell, for this gem :)</span>
  <a data-text-id="7125924546759931049" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


