    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1630945-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1360277823p2/1630945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/102277233?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/1630945-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1630945-alex?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer102277233" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13486280429752984088">According to the author&apos;s note at the back of this book, there are only 2 known facts about Leonardo da Vinci&apos;s mother:<br/><br/>1. Her name was Caterina<br/>2. Leonardo was taken from her the day after his birth to be raised with his father&apos;s family<br/><br/>That is ALL. <br/><br/>And yet somehow, Robin Maxwell took these two facts and weaved an incredible tale of a mother&apos;s love and the lengths she will go to protect her son. I know next to nothing about Leonardo da Vinci, so I don&apos;t know how historically accurate some of the e</span>
  <span id="freeText13486280429752984088" style="display:none">According to the author's note at the back of this book, there are only 2 known facts about Leonardo da Vinci's mother:<br /><br />1. Her name was Caterina<br />2. Leonardo was taken from her the day after his birth to be raised with his father's family<br /><br />That is ALL. <br /><br />And yet somehow, Robin Maxwell took these two facts and weaved an incredible tale of a mother's love and the lengths she will go to protect her son. I know next to nothing about Leonardo da Vinci, so I don't know how historically accurate some of the events with him were. But I loved Caterina's character, and because so little is known about her, Ms. Maxwell was free to create her however she wanted.<br /><br />I really enjoyed this novel!</span>
  <a data-text-id="13486280429752984088" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
